## QA Checks

QA checks automatically highlight all potential translation mistakes before approval.
Detected issues will appear in the proofreading mode.

[x] Enable QA checks

The editor currently has no validation pass before a translation is approved. QA checks
should run automatically when a translation is submitted or when a reviewer opens the
proofreading view. Results should be stored per translation (or computed on-the-fly) and
surfaced as warning badges in LocaleStringList and as an inline panel in EditorCore.

Implementation plan:
1. Define a `QaCheck` interface in `lib/qa/` — takes `{ source, translation, config }`,
   returns `{ type, severity, message }[]`.
2. Implement individual check modules (one file per check category below).
3. Add a `runQaChecks(checks[], source, translation, config)` runner in `lib/qa/index.ts`.
4. Call the runner inside `SuggestStringAction` (after saving) and store results in a
   new `TranslationQaIssue` table (translationId, checkType, severity, message).
5. Expose issues in EditorCore.tsx alongside each translation history entry.
6. Add warning dot to StateIndicator in LocaleStringList when a string has open issues.
7. Add a project-level config object (stored in Project or a new ProjectQaConfig table)
   so admins can toggle individual checks.

Check for:
[x] Empty translation

- Source is empty but the translation is not.
- Translation is empty but the source is not.

Implementation: Simple null/whitespace comparison in `lib/qa/checks/empty.ts`. Run on
every save. High severity.

[x] Length issues

- Translation exceeds predefined length limits. (Limits can be set somewhere)

Context: The `LocaleString` model already has a `maxLength` field. The editor shows a
character counter in `SuggestionForm.tsx` but does not enforce or warn on the limit.

Implementation: Read `maxLength` from the locale string record and emit a warning if
`translation.length > maxLength`. Limit configuration UI belongs in the source file or
per-string settings. Add `maxLength` input to the source file creation dialog once that
exists.

[x] Tags mismatch

- Inconsistent tags in the source and translation.
- ID attributes consistency
- CDATA tag consistency

Implementation: Parse both strings with a lightweight XML/HTML tag extractor in
`lib/qa/checks/tags.ts`. Compare opening/closing tag sets and attribute presence.
Detect `<![CDATA[...]]>` blocks separately.

[x] Spaces mismatch

- Spaces around special symbols
- Start and end spaces
- Start and end new line characters
- Multiple spaces in succession
- Non-breaking spaces

Implementation: Regex-based check in `lib/qa/checks/spaces.ts`. Compare leading/trailing
whitespace between source and translation; scan for `\u00A0` (non-breaking space) and
consecutive space runs.

[x] Variables mismatch

Context: Many projects use placeholder variables like `{name}`, `%s`, `{{count}}`, or
`%(variable)s`. These must appear unchanged in the translation.

Implementation: Extract all variable patterns from source using a configurable regex
(project-level setting). Verify all found variables are present in the translation.
Implement in `lib/qa/checks/variables.ts`.

[x] Punctuation issues

- Inconsistent punctuation in source and translation
- Spacing before and after punctuation marks

Implementation: Check whether terminal punctuation (`.`, `?`, `!`) matches between
source and translation. Check for space-before punctuation (common French vs English
difference). Make locale-aware (some rules differ by target language). Implement in
`lib/qa/checks/punctuation.ts`.

[x] Character case mismatch

- Initial capital letter
- Unexpected multiple capitalized characters in succession

Implementation: Compare first character case. Scan for ALL_CAPS words exceeding a
threshold. Implement in `lib/qa/checks/case.ts`.

[x] Special characters mismatch

- Bracket consistency
- Markup language entities
- Quotes and quote escapes

Implementation: Count and compare bracket pairs `()`, `[]`, `{}`. Parse HTML entities
(`&amp;`, `&lt;`, etc.) and verify they appear in both strings. Check quote pairing.
Implement in `lib/qa/checks/special.ts`.

[ ] Incorrect translation

- Translation marked by project members as incorrect

Context: Reviewers currently have no explicit "mark as incorrect" action — only
Approve and Delete. A "flag as incorrect" button would set a status flag on the
Translation record without deleting it, so the translator can see feedback.

Implementation: Add `flagged` boolean (or `status: FLAGGED`) to the `Translation` model.
Add a "Flag" button in EditorCore alongside the Approve button (visible to REVIEWER+).
Show flagged translations with a warning badge. Include flagged status in QA issues.

[ ] Spelling mistakes

- Detected by integrated spell checker

Context: The browser's built-in `spellcheck` attribute is already present on the
textarea in SuggestionForm.tsx but there is no server-side or integrated checker.

Implementation: Integrate a server-side spell checker (e.g. `nspell` npm package with
language-specific dictionaries) as an optional QA check. Run asynchronously post-save.
Alternatively, document relying on browser spell check and close this item.

[x] Number mismatch

Context: If the source contains numeric values (prices, counts, version numbers), the
translation should typically include the same numbers.

Implementation: Extract all numeric tokens from both strings using a regex. Warn if
source numbers are absent from the translation. Implement in `lib/qa/checks/numbers.ts`.

[ ] Outdated translation

Context: When the source string changes after a translation already exists, that
translation becomes outdated. The `LocaleString` model has an `updatedAt` field and
translations have their own `createdAt` — compare timestamps.

Implementation: In the QA runner, compare `localeString.updatedAt` with
`translation.createdAt`. If the string was updated after the translation was created,
emit an "outdated" warning. Optionally store `sourceHash` on the Translation record
(hash of source content at translation time) for a more robust signal.

---

## Translation Memory / Machine Translation

[ ] Translation Memory - store and reuse previous translations

Context: No TM system exists. Previously approved translations for the same source text
are the natural seed. TM matches should appear as suggestions in EditorCore next to
the current AI/manual suggestions.

Implementation plan:
1. Add a `TranslationMemory` table (projectId, sourceText, targetLang, translatedText,
   createdAt, usageCount) — or query approved `Translation` records directly.
2. On string selection in the editor, query for TM matches above a similarity threshold
   (exact match first, then fuzzy via Levenshtein distance).
3. Expose via `/api/projects/[id]/tm/lookup` endpoint.
4. Render TM hits as clickable suggestions in `EditorCore.tsx` above the input.
5. Add a "Use TM suggestion" action that populates the textarea.

[ ] Machine translation integration (e.g. DeepL, Google Translate)

Context: No MT integration exists. The suggest action in
`app/ui/editor/actions/suggest.ts` is the right place to hook in external MT APIs.

Implementation plan:
1. Add optional env vars: `DEEPL_API_KEY`, `GOOGLE_TRANSLATE_API_KEY`.
2. Create `lib/mt/` adapters (one per provider) implementing a common interface:
   `translate(text, sourceLang, targetLang): Promise<string>`.
3. Add a "Suggest MT translation" button in EditorCore that calls a new server action
   `app/ui/editor/actions/mt-suggest.ts`.
4. Display MT result as a pre-filled suggestion in the textarea (not auto-saved).
5. Store MT provider attribution on the Translation record for audit purposes.

[ ] Pre-translate - fill untranslated strings from TM or MT automatically

Context: Useful for new target languages or after bulk source string updates.

Implementation plan:
1. Add a `POST /api/sourcefiles/[id]/pre-translate` endpoint.
2. Accepts `{ targetLang, strategy: 'TM' | 'MT' | 'TM_THEN_MT' }` in request body.
3. Iterates all untranslated LocaleStrings for the given target language.
4. Fills from TM first (if strategy allows), then falls back to MT.
5. Saves results as Translation records with `approved: false` and a `source` tag
   indicating TM or MT origin.
6. Expose a "Pre-translate" button in the files page (ADMIN+ only).

---

## Export Path Variables (for target path templates in speaky.yaml / UI)

%language% Language name (e.g. Ukrainian)
%two_letters_code% Language code ISO 639-1 (i.e. uk)
%three_letters_code% Language code ISO 639-2/T (i.e. ukr)
%locale% Locale (like uk-UA)
%locale_with_underscore% Locale (i.e. uk_UA)
%android_code% Android Locale identifier used to name "values-" directories
%osx_code% OS X Locale identifier used to name ".lproj" directories
%osx_locale% OS X Locale used to name translated resources (i.e. uk, zh-Hans, zh_HK)
%original_file_name% Original file name
%file_name% File name without extension
%file_extension% Original file extension
%original_path% Use parent folders' names in your project to build the file path in the resulting archive

