## File Format Support

Context: File handlers implement the `FileHandler` interface from `lib/file-handler.ts`
and are registered in `lib/file-handlers/get-handler.ts`. Adding a new format requires
only those two files plus a new handler file — no schema changes needed. The parser type
is stored as a string in the `SourceFile.parser` column.

General implementation steps for each format:
1. Create `lib/file-handlers/<format>.ts` implementing `FileHandler`.
2. Implement `parse(content): ParsedFile` — returns `{ strings: Record<string, string> }`.
3. Implement `serialize(strings, options): string` — converts back to the format.
4. Register the handler in `get-handler.ts`.
5. Add the new parser option to the source file creation UI / `speaky.yaml` docs.

[ ] XLIFF (.xlf / .xliff) — Industry standard; used by many CAT tools.

Context: XLIFF 1.2 and 2.0 are XML-based formats widely used by translation agencies
and tools (memoQ, SDL Trados, Phrase). Supporting XLIFF would allow round-tripping with
professional CAT tools.

Format notes: parse `<trans-unit>` elements (1.2) or `<unit>` elements (2.0); use `id`
attribute as key; `<source>` as source text; `<target>` as translation.
Recommended library: `xliff` npm package.

[ ] GNU Gettext (.po / .pot)

Context: The dominant format for Linux/open-source software. `.pot` files are templates
(source only); `.po` files contain translations. Supports plural forms via `msgid_plural`
/ `msgstr[n]` — plural handling may require schema additions.

Format notes: keys are `msgid` strings; translations are `msgstr`. Use `gettext-parser`
npm package for reliable parsing.

[ ] Android String Resources (strings.xml)

Context: XML format used by Android apps. Keys are the `name` attribute of `<string>`
elements. CDATA wrapping and escape sequences (`\'`, `\"`, `\n`) need special handling.

Format notes: parse with a DOM/SAX XML parser; preserve comments where possible.

[ ] iOS/macOS Strings (.strings)

Context: Key=value text format for Apple platform localization.
Syntax: `"key" = "value";` with `/* comment */` support.

Format notes: implement a simple line-by-line parser; watch for escaped quotes and
newlines within values.

[ ] Java Properties (.properties)

Context: Key=value format used in Java applications and Spring Boot. Supports `\uXXXX`
Unicode escapes and multi-line values with `\` continuation.

Format notes: use the `properties` npm package or implement a small parser following
the Java `Properties` spec.

[ ] YAML (flat and nested)

Context: Used by Ruby on Rails (nested locale files) and many JS/Python projects. The
existing JSON handler already flattens nested keys using `|` as separator
(`lib/file-handlers/json.ts`) — reuse the same `flattenKeys` / `unflattenKeys`
utilities from `lib/utils/key-encode.ts` for YAML.

Format notes: use `js-yaml` npm package. Decide whether to support only flat YAML or
also nested (like Rails `en.yml` format).

